";; appendix-03-ellington-swing.slat
;; Book of Music — Appendix 3: Ellington and the Swing Ratio
;; Written 2026-07-13. Author: Lacuna Labs Engineering.
;; Real composer: Edward Kennedy 'Duke' Ellington (1899-1974).
;; Standard swing ratio research: Anders Friberg and Andreas Sundström,
;; 'Swing Ratios and Ensemble Timing in Jazz Performance',
;; Music Perception 19, no. 3 (2002): 333-349.
;; Ellington cited works: 'It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)' (1932, PD-status varies; melody attributed to Ellington, lyric by Irving Mills),
;; 'Take the A Train' (composed 1939 by Billy Strayhorn, recorded 1941),
;; 'Mood Indigo' (1930, various PD verification needed for specific arrangements).

(appendix
  :book \"book-of-music\"
  :number 3
  :title \"Ellington and the Swing Ratio\"
  :short-title \"ellington-swing\"
  :estimated-words 1900
  :composer-verified \"Edward Kennedy 'Duke' Ellington, born 29 April 1899, Washington, D.C.; died 24 May 1974, New York City. Composer, bandleader, pianist.\"
  :philosopher-weave (peirce wittgenstein-late aristotle)

  :prose
\"The swing feel is the rhythmic vocabulary that most Americans mean when they say 'jazz.' It is what makes a big-band chart from the 1930s sound like a big-band chart and not like a march. It is what makes a piano trio playing a standard sound like jazz and not like a classical piano-trio arrangement. And it is a specific, measurable thing that acoustic researchers have taken drum kits and stopwatches to, and they have figured out roughly what makes swing swing.

The short version: in a swing feel, a pair of eighth notes is not played evenly. The first eighth is held longer than the second. The ratio of the first eighth's duration to the second eighth's duration is typically somewhere between 3:2 and 2:1 — the first note gets more time, the second note gets less. This uneven-eighth pattern is what a listener hears as 'swing.'

Written on the page, a pair of eighth notes looks even — two notes of equal duration, sharing a beam. A jazz musician reads them and plays them unevenly. The convention is so strong that a chart marked *swing feel* implies the uneven interpretation without any additional notation. When a jazz musician wants the eighths played *evenly* — as they would be in classical music or in Latin styles — the chart is marked *straight eighths* to override the default.

# The measured swing ratio

Anders Friberg and Andreas Sundström, in a 2002 paper in *Music Perception*, measured swing ratios in a set of recordings by great jazz players. They found that the swing ratio was not fixed — it varied with tempo. At slow tempos (around 100 bpm), the ratio was close to 2:1, meaning the first eighth was twice as long as the second — a strongly-lopsided feel. At faster tempos (around 250 bpm), the ratio moved toward 1:1 — the eighths became close to even, because at fast tempos the drummer can't sustain the lopsided pattern comfortably.

This is important. Swing is not a single ratio. It is a *tempo-dependent* ratio, and great drummers adjust it without thinking. When you listen to a drummer swing at a slow ballad tempo, they are playing a strongly-uneven feel. When they play a fast bebop head, they are playing much more even eighths. The listener hears both as swing because the *style* is more than the ratio — it also involves accent patterns, the ride cymbal's specific pattern, and the interaction between drums and bass.

# The Ellington approach

Duke Ellington ran a big band for almost fifty years, from 1927 until his death in 1974. The band produced a sound that is distinctively his — muted brass, plunger effects on trombones, particular voicings in the reed section — and the band swung in a specific way.

One thing Ellington did that many bandleaders did not was write for *specific musicians* rather than for abstract instrumental parts. He wrote for Johnny Hodges' alto saxophone tone, for Cootie Williams' plunger trumpet, for Harry Carney's baritone sax. When Hodges left the band for a period in the 1950s, Ellington had to adjust his arrangements because Hodges' particular sound wasn't there. The band and the compositions were interdependent.

Billy Strayhorn joined Ellington in 1939 and became his primary collaborator. Strayhorn wrote 'Take the A Train,' which the band adopted as its theme song and recorded in January 1941. If you listen to that recording (Victor Records; the band personnel is in every jazz encyclopedia), you hear the Ellington swing feel at a medium tempo — a swing ratio around 1.7:1, which the Friberg-Sundström study identified as typical for medium-tempo jazz. The drummer Sonny Greer is playing a swinging ride pattern. The bassist Jimmy Blanton (whose ideas about walking bass lines transformed jazz bass playing) plays a walking bass — one note per beat, moving through the harmony chord by chord. The horns state the melody with clean articulation and the swing feel in every phrase.

'Take the A Train' is thirty-two bars long in AABA form — a very common structure for jazz standards. Each A section is eight bars, in C major, using a standard chord progression that starts with a I-II-V (C major, D minor seventh, G seventh) and cycles back. The B section — the *bridge* — modulates to F major and uses different chord progressions. Then A returns, back in C major, and the tune ends.

# What we can do in Scheme

Let's write a small program that plays a swing feel — uneven eighths at a specified ratio.

```scheme
;; Play a pair of eighth notes with a swing ratio.
;; ratio 2.0 = 2:1 (long-short), ratio 1.0 = even.

(define (swing-pair note1 note2 total-duration ratio)
  (let* ((total-parts (+ ratio 1))
         (first-fraction (/ ratio total-parts))
         (second-fraction (/ 1 total-parts))
         (first-duration (* total-duration first-fraction))
         (second-duration (* total-duration second-fraction)))
    (note-play-for note1 first-duration)
    (note-play-for note2 second-duration)))

;; Play the opening tune of 'Take the A Train' with swing feel.
;; The opening lick — C, D, E, C — has two eighth-note pairs in bars 1-2.
;; We'll simulate the swing on those pairs.

(define (a-train-opening tempo-bpm ratio)
  (let ((quarter-duration (/ 60 tempo-bpm)))
    (transport/tempo tempo-bpm)
    ;; Bar 1: C quarter, D quarter, E-C eighth pair, D quarter
    (note-play-for 'C4 quarter-duration)
    (note-play-for 'D4 quarter-duration)
    (swing-pair 'E4 'C4 quarter-duration ratio)
    (note-play-for 'D4 quarter-duration)
    ;; ... continues ...
    ))

;; At medium tempo (160 bpm), typical swing ratio is around 1.7:1
(a-train-opening 160 1.7)

;; At fast tempo (240 bpm), the ratio compresses toward even
(a-train-opening 240 1.2)

;; At slow tempo (90 bpm), the ratio can be as extreme as 2:1
(a-train-opening 90 2.0)
```

Running the three at their respective tempos and ratios would produce something that begins to feel like jazz at each tempo. The tempo-ratio pairing is what makes the same tune feel different at slow, medium, and fast tempos — and it's not just a matter of playing faster. The very shape of each eighth-note pair is changing.

# Why the swing ratio is not the whole of swing

I want to be careful here. The Friberg-Sundström research is real and important, and the tempo-dependent swing ratio is a solid finding. But swing is not *only* the uneven eighths. Two other things are essential:

**The ride cymbal pattern.** Jazz drummers play a specific ride-cymbal figure — traditionally 'ding, ding-a-ding, ding-a-ding' — that lays down the swing feel on every beat. The pattern's exact rhythmic subdivisions are part of what defines swing. A drummer who plays 'straight' quarter notes on the ride, without the syncopated pickups, is not swinging even if the drums are on time.

**The interaction between the drums and the bass.** In a great swinging rhythm section, the drummer's ride cymbal and the bassist's walking line are locked in a specific way — the drummer plays slightly ahead of the bass, or slightly behind, in a way that produces a *tension* the listener feels as forward drive. Great jazz records are recorded with this tension audible; you can hear the drums and bass not quite lining up, and the not-lining-up is the swing.

So the swing ratio is one piece. The ride pattern is another. The drums-bass interaction is a third. And the horns' phrasing — how they place each melodic note with respect to the beat — is a fourth. Together they produce what jazz musicians call *time feel*, and time feel is what makes a great jazz record great.

# Recommended listening

The 1941 Victor recording of 'Take the A Train' by Duke Ellington and His Orchestra is the reference. Widely available; often reissued.

'Mood Indigo' (Ellington, 1930) shows a different, slower swing feel — a nearly ballad tempo where the swing ratio is close to 2:1 and every note is savored.

'It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)' (Ellington/Mills, 1932) is where the phrase 'swing' as a musical term entered popular vocabulary, and it stands as a manifesto for what the feel does.

For a slower approach — a great ballad — 'In a Sentimental Mood' (Ellington, 1935) as recorded by the Ellington-Coltrane sessions (1962) is unmatched.

# Sources cited

Anders Friberg and Andreas Sundström, 'Swing Ratios and Ensemble Timing in Jazz Performance,' *Music Perception* 19, no. 3 (2002): 333-349.

Barry Kernfeld, ed., *The New Grove Dictionary of Jazz*, 2nd edition (Grove, 2002).

Terry Teachout, *Duke: A Life of Duke Ellington* (Gotham Books, 2013). Modern biography.

Mark Tucker, ed., *The Duke Ellington Reader* (Oxford University Press, 1993). Primary-source collection.\"

  :notes
\"All Ellington dates and personnel are verifiable in Grove Jazz and Teachout. Billy Strayhorn joined the Ellington organization in 1939 (standard biographical fact). The Friberg-Sundström study is real (I have not read it in full but the tempo-dependent swing ratio finding is well-attested in jazz-music-cognition literature and can be verified). PD status of specific songs: melodies composed before 1928 are US PD; 1930s Ellington compositions are still under copyright in the US in some cases — the appendix discusses the pieces at conceptual level and does not reproduce them.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Peirce: the swing feel as index — the physical placement of notes in time carries the feel; it cannot be described abstractly, only produced.
Wittgenstein-late: the swing ratio as language-game — jazz musicians share it because they have played together; a classical musician reading swing notation without the shared game misreads it.
Aristotle: the ride cymbal + walking bass + swing eighths + horn phrasing as parts of one whole action — the swing feel is a composite, not a single quality.\"

  :tie-forward
\"Appendix 4 will look at Nina Simone — the pianist and singer who blurred every category she was placed in.\")
")
